snippet.textDisplay:
They're getting rid of stock and using the refresh as a filler. I don't understand how you didn't see this.
When Ryzen 3000 first came out, the 7 nm process was immature and thus the yields weren't optimal. Thus, AMD took the route of using one high-performance die and one low-performance die for the two dies in Ryzen 3000 CPUs. This is why their overclocking capacity wasn't optimal because it was limited by the low-performance die out of the two dies. Now that the 7 nm process has matured, the yields are good and thus, AMD has no reason to have one die be low-performing in their Ryzen 3000 CPUs. That's why we're expecting a clock boost in their refresh series since their no longer limited by one of their dies being low-performance dies. In addition, even though their process yield is high, they will still have low-performance dies since their yield isn't 100%. I'm assuming that they're using those for the Ryzen 3300 X and 3100 CPUs by disabling the cores with limited clock boost. This is probably why we're seeing such high clocks in 3300 X and 3100 as the low-performing cores are all disabled and thus, only cores that can boost high are active in those CPUs.
There's rumours going around that the 4950X and 4900X will be out in late October this year but the SKUs below that will be closer to new year due to supply issues. This makes sense because AMD usually makes their lower SKUs out of leftover dies that aren't good enough for higher SKUs. I'm assuming that the supply issue is partially caused by the human malware going on right now.
Pushing out Ryzen 3000 refresh is a good way of getting rid of stock to make way for their Ryzen 4000 series, as well as buy time for the possible delay they're facing with the Ryzen 4600~4800X supply, and at the same time have something to compete against Intel's new CPUs.
